				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${k}_{{{{{{\rm{et}}}}}}}=A{{\exp }}[-\frac{{(\Delta G+{\lambda }_{{{{{{\rm{charge}}}}}}})}^{2}}{4{\lambda }_{{{{{{\rm{charge}}}}}}}{k}_{{{{{{\rm{B}}}}}}}T}]$$\end{document}. For the charge transfer among the same molecules (M + M+→M+ + M), ΔG can be approximately zero, and there is an inverse relationship between the rate constant of charge transfer and the charge reorganization energy λcharge. As a result, the molecules with small reorganization energy usually are designed to exhibit excellent charge transport property62. The λcharge can be calculated by the sum of λNS and λCS between the neutral (ground) state (NS) and the charged states (CS) in organic molecules, as shown in Fig. 5c.Fig. 5The relationship between reorganization energy and descriptor.
